# [SLIDE DECK EVOLUTION CHAIN & CORE CONTENT]

## Slide 1: Initialization & Title Cover
- Content: Course title, target audience definition, abstract of the semiconductor evolution chain.
- Theme Backdrop: Introduction of the ATE system context.

## Slide 2: Module 1 — The Physics Interface (ATE Pin Electronics)
- Concepts: Sensors, analog PMUs, power switches (GaN/IGBT), passives (decoupling capacitors, termination resistors).
- ATE Context: How an ATE pin electronics board injects a precise high-speed analog voltage pulse into a DUT (Device Under Test) pin, filters high-frequency noise via passives, and switches high power safely.
- Code Structure: HTML markup linking to external `m1.svg` (Pure line-art signal conditioning block diagram).

## Slide 3: Module 2 — Digital Twin (ATE Digital Channels)
- Concepts: MOSFET transistors as pure binary switches, V_IH/V_IL thresholds representing 1 and 0, logical AND/OR/NOT gates.
- ATE Context: How the ATE instrument reads back a raw electrical voltage wave from the DUT, compares it against programmed threshold windows, and maps it into deterministic 0s and 1s using Boolean logic gates.
- Code Structure: HTML markup linking to external `m2.svg` (Gate-level threshold comparator schematic).

## Slide 4: Module 3 — The Three Mathematical Paradigms (ATE Data Analysis)
- Concepts: Digital exact computing (Binary matching), Analog computing (In-memory hardware accumulation for wave parametric analysis), Probabilistic computing (Stochastic stream yield estimation).
- ATE Context: Different mathematical ways the test engineer processes the millions of raw response matrices coming out of the DUT.
- Code Structure: HTML markup linking to external `m3.svg` (Comparison graph of deterministic vs continuous vs stochastic signal forms).

## Slide 5: Module 4 — Architectural Clash of Kings (The ATE Controller Engine)
- Concepts: Temporal vs. Spatial computing. CPU vs. GPU vs. FPGA vs. ASIC comparison matrix.
- ATE Context:
  - CPU: The main Linux system master controller managing test flow sequences, multi-site databases, and system logs.
  - GPU: Processing massive visual datasets from wafer prober camera alignments and infrared defect detection.
  - FPGA: The programmable Pin Electronics engine. Re-configuring internal hardware routing instantly to match different DUT pinouts without rewiring cables. No fixed instruction set.
  - ASIC: The fixed ultra-high-speed reference driver core handling gigabit test patterns.
- Code Structure: Standardized horizontal geometric table matrix with heavy typographic restraint.

## Slide 6: Module 5 — The Abstraction Elevator (From Test Script to Silicon Snap)
- Concepts: High-level test scripts, OS driver scheduling, Instruction Set Architecture (ISA), Machine code execution, physical transistor flipping.
- ATE Context: Trace the exact vertical cascade from the moment a test engineer clicks "RUN TEST" in a Python IDE down to a single physical pin driver flipping state on the instrument backplane.
- Code Structure: HTML markup linking to external `m5.svg` (The deep vertical abstraction stack block diagram).

